Auto-running MATLAB with RinobotJust like python we can auto-run MATLAB when files appear, but with a small difference.Just select matlab from the command list, choose files to match, and select a matlab script to run.Rinobot will inject an variable filepath into the script so that you can read the file.
Internally Rinobot callsmatlab -nodisplay -nosplash -nodesktop -r "filepath={{filepath}}; run({{your script}}); exit;"
This means that matlab will run without a GUI, and you can access the variable filepath within your script.Full example: plotting dataIn this example we make a simple XY line plot of the data in an incoming file. We take the variable filepath, read the file, plot it and then create a png.[x, y] = textread(filepath);

[pathstr, name, ext] = fileparts(filepath);

set(gcf,'Visible','off');
plot(x, [y]);
print(fullfile(pathstr, [name, '.png']), '-dpng');
If you want to set a defaul value for filepath so your script can be run without Rinobot just usersif ~exist('filepath', 'var')
    filepath = 'some/other/interesting/file.txt';
end
so if the variable filepath does not exist then you can set the variable yourself.
